# Java / Spring Boot Rules

## Package Structure

Every Spring Boot service must follow this layout:

```
com.tams.<service-name>/
├── controller/  — REST controllers only; no business logic
├── service/     — Business logic interfaces and implementations
├── repository/  — Spring Data JPA repositories
├── domain/      — JPA entities
├── dto/         — Request and response DTOs (Java records preferred)
├── config/      — Spring @Configuration classes
├── exception/   — Custom exceptions and @ControllerAdvice handler
├── kafka/       — Kafka producers and consumers (if applicable)
└── client/      — WebClient / RestTemplate wrappers for other services
```

## Dependency Injection

- Use constructor injection exclusively. Never use `@Autowired` on fields.
- Mark injected fields `final`. Use Lombok `@RequiredArgsConstructor` to reduce boilerplate.

## DTOs and API Boundaries

- Every request body and response body must be a dedicated DTO, never a JPA entity.
- Prefer Java records for immutable DTOs: `public record CreateCategoryRequest(String name, BigDecimal minCredit, BigDecimal minEcts) {}`.
- Validate all incoming DTOs with Jakarta Bean Validation (`@NotNull`, `@NotBlank`, `@Positive`, etc.).
- Use `@Valid` on controller method parameters to trigger validation.

## Controllers

- Controllers must delegate to services immediately. A controller method body should be ≤ 10 lines.
- Return `ResponseEntity<T>` with explicit HTTP status codes.
- Group related endpoints in a single controller class annotated with `@RequestMapping`.

## Security

- Every endpoint must be explicitly authorized. Default stance: deny all.
- Use `@PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")` (or equivalent) for role-specific endpoints.
- Never disable CSRF protection without a documented reason (JWT-stateless APIs are exempt).

## Error Handling

- All exceptions must be caught and mapped to structured error responses in a `@ControllerAdvice` class.
- Never let a raw stack trace reach the HTTP response body.
- Use custom exception classes (e.g., `ResourceNotFoundException`, `UnauthorizedException`) instead of generic exceptions.

## Database

- Use Flyway for all schema migrations. Never use `spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=create` or `update` in non-local environments.
- Migration file naming: `V{version}__{description}.sql` (e.g., `V1__create_users_table.sql`).
- Entity primary keys must be UUIDs generated by the database (`DEFAULT gen_random_uuid()`), not auto-increment integers.
- All `TIMESTAMPTZ` columns must default to `NOW()`.

## Build & Dependency Management

- The project uses **Maven**. Do not use Gradle.
- All four Java services (`api-gateway`, `auth-service`, `rule-service`, `analysis-service`) are a **Maven multi-module build** under the root `pom.xml` at `tams/`.
- Each service's `pom.xml` must declare `<parent>` pointing to the root POM with `<relativePath>../../pom.xml</relativePath>`. Never point directly to `spring-boot-starter-parent`.
- Dependency versions are declared once in the root `pom.xml` `<properties>` block. Child POMs must not specify a `<version>` tag.
- Build a single service: `mvn -pl services/auth-service -am package -DskipTests`
- Build all services: `mvn package -DskipTests` from `tams/` root.

## Testing

- Unit tests go in `src/test/java/` mirroring the source package structure.
- Use `@SpringBootTest` + `@AutoConfigureMockMvc` for integration/controller tests.
- Test class naming: `{ClassName}Test` for unit tests, `{ClassName}IT` for integration tests.
- All service-layer methods must have at least one unit test for the happy path and one for the primary failure path.

## Naming

- Packages: `lowercase` (e.g., `com.tams.authservice.controller`)
- Classes: `PascalCase`
- Methods and variables: `camelCase`
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- REST endpoints: lowercase `kebab-case` plural nouns (e.g., `/api/v1/graduation-categories`)
